{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17220"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17220"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9910"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening headache. He reports neck stiffness and sensitivity to light. His partner mentions that he had a generalised seizure two hours ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETemperature: 38.5\u00b0C\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPulse rate: 100/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood pressure: 120/80 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERespiratory rate: 20/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOxygen saturation: 98% on room air\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe appears unwell. Neurological examination reveals neck stiffness but no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giant cell arteritis","Brain tumour","Hypertensive emergency","Meningitis","Intracranial hypotension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Emeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of headache, neck stiffness, photophobia, fever, and seizure in a young adult is highly characteristic of meningeal inflammation. The acute onset and systemic features support an infectious cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less likely:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects people over 50 years and presents with temporal headache, jaw claudication, and visual symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain tumour\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a more gradual onset and would not explain the acute fever and neck stiffness\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive emergency\u003C/strong\u003E requires significantly elevated blood pressure and does not typically cause neck stiffness or photophobia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracranial hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E causes positional headaches that improve when lying flat and does not cause fever or seizures\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of fever, neck stiffness, and altered mental state (seizure) forms the classic triad of meningitis, though not all features need to be present for the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Meningitis classically presents with fever, headache, neck stiffness, and photophobia.","Seizures can occur in meningitis due to cerebral inflammation and irritation.","Young adults with acute onset of meningeal signs require urgent investigation for meningitis."],"references":["Runde TJ, Anjum F, Hafner JW. Bacterial Meningitis. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470351/","Hasbun R. Progress and Challenges in Bacterial Meningitis: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Dec 6;328(21):2147-2154. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.20521. Erratum in: JAMA. 2023 Feb 14;329(6):515. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.0570. PMID: 36472590.","Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17220"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:55:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:56:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71207"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cr